# libFuzzer dictionary (issue #359): little-endian byte encodings of
# boundary/edge-case constants for every value width the AST fuzzer
# generates (Types.hpp's TypeId/ALL_TYPES).
#
# These are exactly the operand values that trigger overflow/UB-boundary/
# rounding miscompiles (INT_MIN, -1, powers of two, NaN, +-inf, +-0.0,
# subnormals, epsilons), and -- per Ast.hpp's Kind::Const / packImm<T> --
# libFuzzer's mutator can only splice one in deliberately if the exact byte
# pattern is in its dictionary; drawing 4-8 specific bytes uniformly at
# random to hit one by chance is vanishingly unlikely (see README.md
# "Known findings" for a documented case: the signed-zero negation bug was
# essentially unreachable until an unrelated change made 0.0 common via
# buffer-exhaustion zero-padding).
#
# This is a plain "splice these bytes somewhere" token list, NOT an encoding
# of a full ByteReader-decodable program (that's corpus/ -- see
# SeedGen.cpp/README.md "Regenerating the seed corpus"): libFuzzer inserts
# dictionary tokens at arbitrary offsets, so a token landing inside a
# Kind::Const leaf's `reader.consume<T>()` window reproduces one of these
# constants; a token landing elsewhere just perturbs generation like any
# other mutation.
#
# Each entry's bytes are `std::numeric_limits<T>::{min,max,epsilon,...}` (or
# a literal 0/1/-1/power-of-two) memcpy'd little-endian into sizeof(T) bytes
# -- exactly ByteReader::consume<T>() (ByteReader.hpp) / Types.hpp::packImm.
# These values never change for a given T, so the list below is stable and
# was derived once; there is no generator to re-run (unlike corpus/, whose
# programs depend on Ast.hpp's Kind tables -- see SeedGen.cpp).

# --- 8-bit integers ---
i8_min="\x80"
i8_max="\x7f"
